eweave/harmonic_planner.py`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+- `ESCALATIONS.md`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+## Correctness\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+The implementation of `transpose_to_key(record, key_name) -> int` correctly computes the smallest semitone offset required to align a sample's detected pitch with the nearest in-key pitch class. It handles the octave wrap correctly by searching in both directions. The tie-breaking logic favors negative transposition, which is consistent and verified by tests.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+## Completeness\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+All acceptance criteria are met:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+- Transposition maps `pitch_hz` to the nearest in-key pitch using the artist's B-rooted palette.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+- Samples with `pitch_confidence < 0.4` or `pitch_hz <= 0` return 0 semitones, correctly playing \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"atonally\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+- Tests cover known pitch/key combinations, low-confidence pass-through, and octave wrap shortest-path selection.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+## Consistency\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+The implementation leverages `harmonic_planner.py` for canonical key normalization and scale definitions, ensuring consistency with the rest of the SenseWeave harmony engine. The coding style and test patterns match the existing codebase.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+## Security\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+No security vulnerabilities were identified. The implementation uses standard math libraries and does not involve unsafe operations or credential handling.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+## Quality\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+The code is concise, well-documented, and follows idiomatic Python patterns. The tests are comprehensive and use appropriate fixtures (standard within the project). Mandatory hardening checks regarding `bootstrap_identity` were found to be already addressed in the daemon startup flows (`daemon.py` and `cypherclaw_daemon.py`).\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n+## Issues Found\\\\\\